{
  format: 1
  name: descriptor-bytes-encoding
  suite: scenario
  spec: ["#blobs", "§18.1", "#annex-a", "§A.1"]
  tags: ["blob", "identity"]
  note: '''
    Resolution of the apparent §18.1 contradiction (SPEC-ISSUES #20). The worked
    descriptor encodes the byte count as a JSON *string* ("$bytes": "184320")
    while the prose calls $bytes "a non-negative integer byte count". These do not
    conflict: Annex A.1 pins the canonical wire value of `int` as a JSON string
    with canonical base-10 digits, so the string form IS the canonical spelling of
    the integer, and the prose merely names the logical type. A client declaring
    $bytes as the canonical string "5" for 5 bytes of content is therefore valid;
    the descriptor verifies and the containing mutation commits (ok). A bare JSON
    number would be the only non-string int on the wire and is non-canonical.

    Not surfaceable here (acknowledged on the scenario ledger): a *verifying*
    client-declared descriptor must bind into the mutation call, which the honest-
    only blob parameter does not expose, and the harness's DeclaredDescriptor
    carries the byte count as a decoded integer, erasing the string-vs-number wire
    spelling this case pins.
  '''

  package: {
    $liasse: 1
    $app: "t.blobs.bytesenc@1.0.0"
    $model: {
      stores: {
        $key: "id"
        id: "text"
        connector: "text"
        enabled: "bool = true"
      }
      docs: {
        $key: "id"
        $blob_storage: { $in: "/stores['primary']" }
        id: "text"
        file: {
          $type: "blob"
          $max_bytes: "10485760"
          $media: ["text/plain"]
        }
      }
      $mut: {
        add: [
          "doc = .docs + { id: @id, file: @file }"
          "return doc { id }"
        ]
      }
      $public: { docs: { $mut: { add: ".add" } } }
    }
    $data: { stores: { primary: { connector: "fs-a" } } }
  }

  hosts: {
    connectors: { "fs-a": { capabilities: ["stream_upload", "checksum"] } }
  }

  steps: [
    { connect: "c1" }
    { blob_put: {
        call: "public.docs.add"
        param: "file"
        args: { id: "d1" }
        content: "hello"
        media: "text/plain"
        // Canonical int wire form of the byte count: a JSON string (Annex A.1),
        // as in the §18.1 worked example.
        claim: { $bytes: "5" }
        on: "c1"
      }
      expect: { outcome: ok, value: { id: "d1" } } }
  ]
}
